 Check if a number has only one bit set 
Approach:
âœ… Step 1: Check if number is positive
The number must be greater than 0.
If itâ€™s 0 or negative â†’ it cannot have only one bit set.
âœ…Step 2: Use this bitwise trick
For a number n, do:
n & (n - 1)
If the result is 0 â†’ it means only one bit is set.
//code
public class Main {
    
    // Method to check one-bit set
    public boolean oneBitSet(String numStr) {
        int n = Integer.parseInt(numStr);
        
        if (n <= 0) return false;
        
        return (n & (n - 1)) == 0;
    }
    
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Main t = new Main();
        
        System.out.println(t.oneBitSet("8")); // true
        System.out.println(t.oneBitSet("6")); // false
    }
}
// ðŸš€ Toggle Bits in a Range
    Input : n=50;L=2; R=4;
   Output: Original number: 50
    Number after toggling bits from 2 to 4: 60
Approach:
âœ…Create a mask with 1s between L and R, then XOR it with n to flip those bits.
âœ…((1 << R) - 1) ^ ((1 << (L-1)) - 1)
//code
public class toggleBitsInRange
{
	public static int toggleBitsInRange(int n,int L,int R) {
	int mask=((1<<R)-1)^((1<<(L-1))-1);
	return n^mask;
	}
	public static void main(String[] args){
	    int n=50;
	    int L=2;
	    int R=4;
	      int result = toggleBitsInRange(n, L, R);
	    System.out.println("Original No."+n);
	    System.out.println("Number of after toggleBitsInRange"+L+"to"+R+":"+result);
	}
} 
// Sum of XORs of all pairs in an array
âœ… Approach:

1ï¸âƒ£ Shift 1 left by bit positions
â†’ (1 << bit) creates a mask where only the bit-th position is 1.
2ï¸ AND the mask with num
â†’ num & (1 << bit) isolates that specific bit in num.
3ï¸âƒ£ Check if result is not zero
â†’ If non-zero, that bit in num is set (i.e. itâ€™s 1); otherwise itâ€™s not set (i.e. itâ€™s 0).
public class SumOfXORs {
    public static int sumXOR(int[] arr) {
        int n = arr.length;
        int total = 0;

        for (int bit = 0; bit < 32; bit++) {
            int countSet = 0;

            for (int num : arr) {
                if ((num & (1 << bit)) != 0) {
                    countSet++;
                }
            }

            int countUnset = n - countSet;
            int pairs = countSet * countUnset;
            int contribution = pairs * (1 << bit);

            total += contribution;
        }

        return total;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] arr = {1, 2, 3};
        System.out.println(sumXOR(arr)); // Output â†’ 6
    }
}
